<ChannelTradeLayout
  title="AI WhatsApp for Flat Roofers & GRP Specialists | Rapid Receptionist"
  description={`AI WhatsApp for UK flat roofers and GRP specialists. Responds to ponding photos, builder extension requests, and EPDM repair enquiries while you laminate. Add-on at £${pricing.addOn.price}/month.`}
  canonicalUrl="/flat-roofers/ai-whatsapp/"
  channelName="AI WhatsApp"
  tradeName="Flat Roofer"
  tradeNamePlural="Flat Roofers & GRP Specialists"
  tradeSlug="flat-roofers"
  headline="AI WhatsApp for Flat Roofer & GRP Specialist Companies"
  accentWord="Flat Roofing"
  subhead="A builder WhatsApps at 7am on a Wednesday with two photos. He has just completed the timber frame and plywood deck for a single-storey side return extension on a terraced house in Cowley — the photos show 18mm WBP plywood screwed across the joists, the wall plate trimmed neatly, and the existing house wall exposed on one side for the upstand. His message: 'Morning — side return extension in Cowley. Deck is down, plywood, about 16 square metres. Need GRP fibreglass with a warm roof build-up. Architect wants 80mm Celotex, VCL, GRP topcoated in dark grey. Upstand against the house wall on the left side and back. Drip edge trim at the front into the gutter. Can you measure and price today? My window fitter is in next Monday and needs a weathertight roof above him. Photos attached.' You are loading the van with resin drums, CSM rolls, and acetone for today's bay window GRP job in Marston. Both hands on the resin containers. Without AI WhatsApp, the text waits until the first tea break at 9:30. He messages two other GRP installers; one confirms by 7:45. With it, the AI responds at 7:01am, asks whether the joists run parallel or perpendicular to the fall direction, and captures the lead — Cowley side return, 16 sqm, plywood deck, 80mm Celotex warm roof, VCL, GRP dark grey topcoat, upstand left and rear, drip edge front, window fitter Monday."
  scenario="It is 9pm on a Sunday. A homeowner in Charlbury has been watching a blister on her GRP flat roof grow over three months. Tonight she photographed it from the landing window — a raised area about 300mm across on the topcoat surface, the grey finish cracked around the edge. She also photographed the inside — a corresponding damp patch on the ceiling below, lighter brown but clearly moisture. She WhatsApps three GRP firms: 'Hi — we have a GRP fibreglass roof on our kitchen extension that is about 7 years old. There is a blister forming on the surface — about the size of a dinner plate — and the topcoat is cracking around it. Inside, there is a damp mark on the ceiling directly below. Is this something you can repair or does the whole roof need redoing? The extension is about 4 metres by 3 metres. It was done by the builder who did the extension but I do not think he was a specialist. Photos attached. Charlbury, OX7.' Without AI WhatsApp, you see the message Monday morning. One firm replied at 9:20pm. With AI WhatsApp, the reply arrives at 9:01pm: 'Thank you for the photos — blistering with cracked topcoat after seven years can indicate trapped moisture between the laminate layers, often from the original installation. Could you confirm whether the blister feels soft or hard when pressed, and whether the roof has any areas where water sits after rain?' She confirms soft blister and ponding at the back. Monday you call: GRP extension, Charlbury OX7, 7 years old, 4x3m, blistering with cracked topcoat, soft blister, damp underneath, ponding rear, non-specialist original installation."
  benefits={benefits}
  faqs={faqs}
  channelPageUrl="/construction-trades/ai-whatsapp/"
  tradePageUrl="/flat-roofers/ai-receptionist/"
  ctaHeadline="Confirm the Cowley Side Return While You Load the Resin Drums"
  ctaSubhead={`A builder's deck is down and the window fitter arrives Monday. The AI captured the warm roof specification while you loaded the van. Add-on at £${pricing.addOn.price}/month.`}
